            <div class="pt-2">
                <p>The PHP $_GET is a PHP superglobal which is used to collect form data after submitting an HTML form using method="get". Information sent from an HTML form with the GET method is displayed in the browser's address bar making it less secure than POST.</p>
                <p>Let's assume we have an HTML form that takes name and email as input and sends it to another file named "name_get.php". We can access the values of "name_get.php" with the $_GET superglobal.</p>
                <p><strong>HTML FORM</strong></p>
                <pre class="bg-black text-white p-2"><code>&lt;html&gt;
&lt;body&gt;

&lt;form action="name_get.php" method="get"&gt;
  Name: &lt;input type="text" name="name"&gt;
  Email: &lt;input type="text" name="email"&gt;
  &lt;input type="submit"&gt;
&lt;/form&gt;

&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;</code></pre>
            <p><strong>name_get.php</strong></p>
            <pre class="bg-black text-white p-2"><code>&lt;html&gt;
&lt;body&gt;

Welcome &lt;?php echo $_GET["name"]; ?&gt;!<br>
Your email address is &lt;?php echo $_GET["email"]; ?&gt;

&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;</code></pre>
                <p><strong>Output:</strong></p>
                <pre class="bg-black text-white p-2"><code>Welcome Harry!
Your email address is harry@example.com</code></pre>
